#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:6
msgid "Introduction to byte ordering and ndarrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:8
msgid ""
"The ``ndarray`` is an object that provides a python array interface to data "
"in memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:11
msgid ""
"It often happens that the memory that you want to view with an array is not "
"of the same byte ordering as the computer on which you are running Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:15
msgid ""
"For example, I might be working on a computer with a little-endian CPU - "
"such as an Intel Pentium, but I have loaded some data from a file written by "
"a computer that is big-endian.  Let's say I have loaded 4 bytes from a file "
"written by a Sun (big-endian) computer.  I know that these 4 bytes represent "
"two 16-bit integers.  On a big-endian machine, a two-byte integer is stored "
"with the Most Significant Byte (MSB) first, and then the Least Significant "
"Byte (LSB). Thus the bytes are, in memory order:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:23
msgid "MSB integer 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:24
msgid "LSB integer 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:25
msgid "MSB integer 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:26
msgid "LSB integer 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:28
msgid ""
"Let's say the two integers were in fact 1 and 770.  Because 770 = 256 * 3 + "
"2, the 4 bytes in memory would contain respectively: 0, 1, 3, 2. The bytes I "
"have loaded from the file would have these contents:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:36
msgid ""
"We might want to use an ``ndarray`` to access these integers.  In that case, "
"we can create an array around this memory, and tell numpy that there are two "
"integers, and that they are 16 bit and big-endian:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:47
msgid ""
"Note the array ``dtype`` above of ``>i2``.  The ``>`` means 'big-"
"endian' (``<`` is little-endian) and ``i2`` means 'signed 2-byte integer'.  "
"For example, if our data represented a single unsigned 4-byte little-endian "
"integer, the dtype string would be ``<u4``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:52
msgid "In fact, why don't we try that?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:58
msgid ""
"Returning to our ``big_end_arr`` - in this case our underlying data is big-"
"endian (data endianness) and we've set the dtype to match (the dtype is also "
"big-endian).  However, sometimes you need to flip these around."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:64
msgid ""
"Scalars do not include byte order information, so extracting a scalar from "
"an array will return an integer in native byte order.  Hence:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:70
msgid ""
"NumPy intentionally does not attempt to always preserve byte-order and for "
"example converts to native byte-order in `numpy.concatenate`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:74
msgid "Changing byte ordering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:76
msgid ""
"As you can imagine from the introduction, there are two ways you can affect "
"the relationship between the byte ordering of the array and the underlying "
"memory it is looking at:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:80
msgid ""
"Change the byte-ordering information in the array dtype so that it "
"interprets the underlying data as being in a different byte order. This is "
"the role of ``arr.newbyteorder()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/byteswapping.rst:83
msgid ""
"Change the byte-ordering of the underlying data, leaving the dtype "
"interpretation as it was.  This is what ``arr.byteswap()`` does."
msgstr ""

